### Astro Static Site Generation with Strapi Data

Source: https://context7_llms

Fetches articles from Strapi using getStaticPaths to generate static pages for each article. It maps fetched articles to route parameters and passes article data as props. This is suitable for SSG where content is known at build time.

```astro
---
import fetchApi from '../../lib/strapi';
import type Article from '../../interfaces/article';


export async function getStaticPaths() {
  const articles = await fetchApi<Article[]>({
    endpoint: 'articles',
    wrappedByKey: 'data',
  });


  return articles.map((article) => ({
    params: { slug: article.slug },
    props: article,
  }));
}
type Props = Article;


const article = Astro.props;
---


<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <title>{article.title}</title>
  </head>


  <body>
    <main>
      <img src={import.meta.env.STRAPI_URL + article.image.data.url} />


      <h1>{article.title}</h1>


      <p>{article.content}</p>
      <MyMarkdownComponent>
        {article.content}
      </MyMarkdownComponent>
      <Fragment set:html={article.content} />
    </main>
  </body>
</html>
```

--------------------------------

### Generate Static Routes with getStaticPaths() in Astro

Source: https://context7_llms

The `getStaticPaths()` function generates multiple, prerendered page routes from a single .astro component. It returns an array of objects, each containing `params` to define URL paths and optionally `props` to pass data to the page template. This is used for routes created at build time (static site generation).

```astro
---
// In 'server' mode, opt in to prerendering:
// export const prerender = true


export async function getStaticPaths() {
  return [
    // { params: { /* required */ }, props: { /* optional */ } },
    { params: { post: '1' } }, // [post] is the parameter
    { params: { post: '2' } }, // must match the file name
    // ...
  ];
}
---
<!-- Your HTML template here. -->
```

### Generating pages > Static site generation

Source: https://docs.astro.build/llms-full.txt

If you are using Astro’s default static site generation, you will use [dynamic routes](/en/guides/routing/#dynamic-routes) and the `getStaticPaths` function to generate your project pages.

Create a new directory `src/pages/blog/` and add a new file called `[...slug].astro` with the following code:

--------------------------------

### Static site generation

Source: https://context7_llms

This section demonstrates how to leverage Astro's Static Site Generation (SSG) mode to create dynamic blog post pages. The process involves creating a file named `[slug].astro` within the `/src/pages/blog/` directory. This file must export a function called `getStaticPaths`. This function is responsible for fetching all necessary data, in this case, blog posts, from a content management system like Kontent.ai. The fetched data will then be used to generate individual pages for each blog post.

--------------------------------

### Generating individual blog posts > Static site generation

Source: https://context7_llms

The `getStaticPaths()` function plays a crucial role in Astro's static site generation. It's responsible for generating a list of all possible paths that Astro will turn into pages during the build process. For dynamic routes, like the `[slug].astro` file used for individual blog posts, this function fetches the data needed to create each unique page. It maps the fetched entries to objects that include `params` (to define the URL segment, e.g., the blog post's slug) and `props` (to pass data directly to the page component). This ensures that each blog post gets its own dedicated URL and displays its specific content.

### Animating Transforms with GSAP v3 Aliases

Source: https://gsap.com/docs/v3/GSAP/CorePlugins/CSS

Illustrates the use of GSAP v3's built-in aliases for animating CSS transforms. These aliases provide a more performant and consistent way to animate transforms compared to manually constructing the transform string. GSAP ensures a consistent order of operations for transforms: translation, scale, rotationX, rotationY, skew, and rotationZ.

```javascript
gsap.to(element, {
  // writing out the transform string 🔥
  // transform: "translate(-50%,-50%)"
  xPercent: -50,
  yPercent: -50,
});
```

--------------------------------

### Configure force3D for GSAP Performance

Source: https://gsap.com/docs/v3/GSAP/CorePlugins/CSS

Explains the `force3D` property in GSAP, which defaults to 'auto' for optimizing performance by using `translate3d()` and compositor layers. It shows how to explicitly set `force3D` to `true` or `false` to control 2D/3D mode.

```javascript
// To keep it in 3D mode, you can set force3D: true.
// Or, to stay in 2D mode whenever possible, set force3D: false.
gsap.to(element, {
  duration: 1,
  rotationX: 45,
  force3D: true // or false, or "auto" (default)
});
```

--------------------------------

### GSAP v3 Lazy Rendering Control Example (JavaScript)

Source: https://gsap.com/docs/v3/GSAP/Tween/vars

Shows how to control lazy rendering in GSAP v3 using the 'lazy' property. By default, GSAP delays writing animation values until the end of a tick for performance. Setting 'lazy: false' disables this for a specific tween.

```javascript
gsap.to(".element", {
  x: 500,
  duration: 2,
  lazy: false // Disables lazy rendering for this tween
});
```

--------------------------------

### Optimize Morph SVG Performance with Predefined shapeIndex

Source: https://gsap.com/docs/v3/Plugins/MorphSVGPlugin

Explains how to improve MorphSVG performance by defining a numeric shapeIndex in advance, bypassing the automatic calculations. The 'log' value for shapeIndex can be used to output the automatically calculated index to the console, which can then be manually applied for optimization.

```javascript
// logs a value like "shapeIndex:[3]"
gsap.to("#id", {
  duration: 1,
  morphSVG: { shape: "#otherID", shapeIndex: "log" },
});
// now you can grab the value from the console and drop it in...
gsap.to("#id", {
  duration: 1,
  morphSVG: { shape: "#otherID", shapeIndex: [3] },
});
```

### CSS > Transforms > Deep Dive - Why use shorthand transforms?

Source: https://gsap.com/docs/v3/GSAP/CorePlugins/CSS

Using GSAP's shorthand transform properties (like `x: 50`) is recommended over animating the transform string (e.g., `transform: "translateX(50px)"`). When animating a string, GSAP must parse the browser's generated `matrix()` or `matrix3d()` value, which is computationally intensive. The string format can also lead to unpredictable results due to CSS's strict order of operations. With shorthand properties, GSAP directly handles each value, leading to significant performance gains, optimizations, and a more intuitive, consistent order of operations.

